{{Top|real|italics=1}}
'''''The One Man Star Wars Trilogy''''' is an Off-Broadway play based on the [[Original trilogy|original ''Star Wars'' trilogy]], written and performed by Canadian actor Charles Ross, and directed by [[Wikipedia:TJ Dawe|TJ Dawe]]. It premiered in [[Wikipedia:Toronto|Toronto]], [[Wikipedia:Ontario|Ontario]] in [[January]] [[2001]], and has since toured worldwide, with over 1,000 performances in 119 cities as of [[March]] [[2007]].<ref name="SMHblog">{{WebCite|url=http://blogs.smh.com.au/entertainment/archives/club_metro/010366.html|text=How I invented One Man Star Wars|author=Ross, Charles|date=2007-03-15|archivedate=20070319202018}}</ref> The show is licensed by [[Lucasfilm]],<ref name="HSW5">{{WebCite|url=http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/arts/theater/one-man-star-wars4.htm|text=How the One Man Star Wars Trilogy Works (part 5)|author=Wolson, Tracy V.|archivedate=20160721191403}}</ref> and has been performed at [[Celebration III]],<ref>{{SWArchive|url=community/event/celebration/news20041101.html|text=Star Wars: Community - One Man Star Wars Trilogy at Celebration III}}</ref> [[Celebration IV]],<ref>{{SWArchive|url=community/event/celebration/news20070228.html|text=One Man ''Star Wars'' Trilogy for Celebration IV}}</ref> [[Celebration Europe (2007)|Celebration Europe]]<ref>{{SWArchive|url=community/event/celebration/f20070706/index.html|text=The Insider's Guide to Celebration Europe}}</ref> and [[Celebration V]].<ref>{{SWArchive|url=fans/events/cv_charlie_ross/index.html|text=One Man ''Star Wars'' Trilogy at Celebration V}}</ref>

==Description==
The play runs for 75 minutes (although earlier incarnations lasted for one hour) and has only one cast member. Charles Ross plays all the characters, recreates the effects, inserts factoids when appropriate, sings from the [[John Williams]] score, flies the ships, and fights both sides of the battles. The inspiration came from playing Frisbee with friends; the thrower would say a line from the movies, and the catcher had to say the following line while catching.<ref name="HSW1">{{WebCite|url=http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/arts/theater/one-man-star-wars.htm|text=How the One Man Star Wars Trilogy Works (part 1)|author=Wolson, Tracy V.|archivedate=20170914003231}}</ref> His impersonation of [[R2-D2/Legends|R2-D2]] has been described as "spot on,"<ref>{{WebCite|url=http://www.theatermania.com/content/news.cfm/story/6487|text=One-Man Star Wars Trilogy - New York Review|author=Klasfeld, Adam|date=2005-08-10|archivedate=20080624221324}}</ref> but Ross himself has said, "I've always thought my [[Yoda/Legends|Yoda]] voice sounded too much like a goblin sucking helium."<ref name="SW-Comiccon">{{SWArchive|url=community/event/con/f20040720/indexp6.html|text=Comic-Con International 2004 - A Cast of Thousands In One: Charlie Ross}}</ref> Ross has purportedly seen the original movie over 400 times.

Ross has also used the concept with other film trilogies, including The One Man The Lord of the Rings, which was performed from 2004 to 2005. He was asked to stop performing by the intellectual property holder.<ref name="SMHblog" />

==Performances==
Ross's show has gone from a piece performed mostly at [[Wikipedia:Fringe theatre|fringe festivals]] to a touring show with sold-out crowds and television appearances. Aside from the various [[Celebration|''Star Wars'' Celebrations]], Ross has been on [[NBC]]'s [[Wikipedia:Late Night with Conan O'Brien|Late Night with Conan O'Brien]], [[Wikipedia:Craig Ferguson|Craig Ferguson]], [[Wikipedia:The Today Show|The Today Show]] and [[CBS]]'s [[Wikipedia:Late Late Show|Late Late Show]]. Ross has performed the show for [[Wikipedia:Vin Diesel|Vin Diesel]] and the rest of the cast on the set of [[Wikipedia:The Chronicles of Riddick|The Chronicles of Riddick]],<ref name="HSW5" /> at the world science fiction convention masquerade half time show ([[Wikipedia:Noreascon|Noreascon]]) in 2004, and [[Wikipedia:Comic-Con|Comic-Con]] International 2004 in [[Wikipedia:San Diego, CA|San Diego, CA]].<ref name="SW-Comiccon" />

